label chapter4:

    # [Scene: Dune Gardens | Low Tide Morning]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Brisk, driving strings with a buoyant percussion—hope in motion]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Gulls calling; the wet slap of boots; trowel scraping peat]
    "You chose the mud. You chose the scraping cold of the seedlings between your fingers and the steady ache in your forearms that comes from doing one honest thing over and over. Your field jacket is"
    "already darkened at the cuffs; your hair is twisted into a practical knot that keeps escaping in the salt wind. The notebook is folded into an inside pocket, but the pages live in your head now—numbers,"
    "expected attenuation, root mass versus sediment capture—far less tidy than the neat sketches you used to make on campuses where failure didn't mean a neighbor's house."
    "Rin Sato is up to their elbows in peat a few meters away, sleeves rolled, a smear of turquoise paint across a knuckle from last night's banner. They grin when they see you, and the world"
    "rearranges by a fraction of degree: the ridge of their cheek, the way the light glances off their undercut, how alive their hands are when they hand you a handful of dune grass seedlings."
    show rin_sato at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rin_sato "Here — for you. These are the cordgrass plugs. They'll knit the terraces if we plant them tight, like stitches."
    "You accept the seedlings. The stems are brittle and colder than you expect; mud presses into the skin under your nails. For a moment your scientist's voice is a whisper behind your teeth: root density, expected"
    "percent cover, the time constant until the first measurable tidal dampening. Then you put that list away and find language that stitches to the hands around you."

    "You tell them where to press, how deep, how to angle each crown toward the incoming flow. Your fingers move on muscle memory—hard-won and local—and your explanations come out plain, clipped into little stories" "Plant like little fingers holding the bank,' you say, 'then the roots do the rest."

    rin_sato "You always turn math into stories,' they say, half-teasing, half in awe. 'My grandmother would have liked that."
    show alea_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    alea_maren "Grandmothers and equations both want the same thing—something that keeps on steadying."
    "Tomas lugs a cedar post up the shallow channel and drops it with a grunt. Mud sprays. Maya arrives with a thermos and a loaf wrapped in oilcloth; steam ghosts the air. The project hums: you stake, measure, and backfill; someone reads a line level aloud like a chant."
    show tomas_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_reyes "Hey Alea, you're stealing my precision. Don't get me wrong—I'm loving it."
    hide rin_sato
    show maya_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_calder "Bread?' (She wedges the thermos into the crook of her arm and offers sliced pieces.) 'You can talk science with carbs now."

    alea_maren "Please."
    "The yeast warms up the cold, and for a minute your chest unclenches."

    menu:
        "Take the seedlings and tuck one into your notebook as a keepsake":
            "You press a single root-stem against the inside cover, already thinking of the coordinate scribble beside it. It feels like a pact. Rin nudges you with a grin and plants another bundle deeper into the marsh, their laugh mixing with the gulls."
        "Hand the seedlings back to Rin and focus on the elevation readings":
            "You hand them back with a precise index finger, and your attention snaps to the line level. Numbers matter here—you murmur the expected attenuation percentage. Rin listens, then turns your sentence into something softer for the volunteers, making the math sound like a promise rather than a forecast."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue with the montage and subsequent scene as written."
    hide alea_maren
    hide tomas_reyes
    hide maya_calder

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A rhythmic tapping—stakes being pounded—rising like a chorus]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swells; strings climb with quick staccato notes]
    "Hours condense into a forward motion. The terraced reed trap you designed catches its first wrinkle of silt; a small, filthy triumph. You check the early tidal attenuation figures on your handheld log: a modest but"
    "honest drop in peak velocity through the planted channels. You jot the numbers and feel them bloom into something you can show—something that feels like leverage in polite meetings."
    "The data is messy, but it's ours. It binds your training to their hands and their songs."
    "Rin Sato moves through the volunteers translating your sentences. Where you say 'root biomass' they say 'a web of little roots that catches the ocean's breath and tucks it into the mud.' A neighbor who never"
    "came to your town hall meetings repeats Rin's line to a child as they plant; the child believes it like a bedtime story. That line—your science, turned into story—travels faster than you ever did with a"
    "powerpoint."
    show rin_sato at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rin_sato "Listen,' they say, kneeling close, 'you're good at this. You don't have to carry the whole town in your head at once."
    show alea_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    alea_maren "I know what failure costs.' (The sentence is small but solid.) 'I don't want to be the person who gave hope without a plan."

    rin_sato "You don't have to be the only person with a plan. Let us be in the plan with you."
    "The marsh answers with small miracles: a plug takes easier than you expected; silt rides into a shallow pocket you didn't imagine would hold. Volunteers clap like people who have found their voices again. The project feels like a choir—each individual note weak alone, glorious together."

    "Maya (laughing)" "All right, choir director—bring back the kids' chorus next week. We need songs for planting."

    alea_maren "I'll write a lyric about flux and sediment transport."
    hide rin_sato
    hide alea_maren

    scene bg ch4_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant traffic and the hum of a speaker from the promenade; a polished voice advertises 'SAFE SOLUTIONS' over a loop]
    "You notice Elias Hart's campaign ads along the promenade—slick graphics promising immediate protection in bronze-voiced soundbites. They are a thin film over the town's roughness: high-polish assurances that make your stomach tighten. For a flash, the"
    "joy frays at the edges with the knowledge that the tide of capital and narrative runs differently from the tide under your boots."
    "His promises are tempting to people with mortgages and businesses. The ads are the counterpoint to your afternoon; they make the stakes sharper."
    "But the afternoon refuses to collapse into cynicism. As dusk bleeds in, Maya hauls lanterns out of the cafe van; stringed lights are passed hand to hand like a relay. The pier is lined not with"
    "corporate floodlight but with warm, jarred flames and low songs; neighbors bring small instruments. There is a rawness to it—no microphones, only bodies leaning forward to be heard."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Folk ensemble—bodhrán, fiddle—simple, swelling in the gaps between lantern light]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Children shouting; a distant bell; wavelets kissing the pier pilings]
    "Rin Sato stands beside you at the edge of the pier, shoulders brushing. For the first time today, the calculations don't run behind every thought. You laugh—really laugh—when they shrug a spray of salt from their"
    "hair and trail their fingers along your forearm in a gesture that is all light, all permission."
    show rin_sato at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rin_sato "Alea,' they say, and they don't use your title or your last name. They use something softer. 'Alea. You stayed."
    "The name is a small bell. It rings against all the colder things you've kept safe behind measurements and margins. When they say your name like that—unadorned and steady—you feel a thread loosen, one you had tied off years ago to keep yourself whole."

    rin_sato "We made something today that might hold. Not forever. Not perfectly. But enough to buy breath."
    show alea_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    alea_maren "Enough to buy more work."
    "The pier becomes a constellation of small bright commitments: a neighbor promises to teach seed-saving, Tomas volunteers to ferry more posts next week, Maya plans a supper where people can draft mutual-aid plans. The town's chorus"
    "crescendos into a song you can hum the rhythm of in your bones—the possibility of collective action."

    menu:
        "Step forward and start the group's chant—'Plant, bind, breathe'":
            "You take a breath and you lead. Your voice finds pitch; others join. The chant turns work into ritual, and you feel, for a carve of night, the weight of the world shift away from your shoulders onto a hundred hands."
        "Stay beside Rin and record tonight's attenuation number in your notebook":
            "You flip open the notebook and write: 'ΔV = -7% over planted channels (preliminary)'. Numbers anchor you in the honest work; Rin hums the melody of the chant, and you let the sound sit with the figures like salt on a wound healing."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue with the closing ceremony and subsequent reflections as written."
    hide rin_sato
    hide alea_maren

    scene bg ch4_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The tide, slow and patient; a hush that is nearly reverent]
    "You let yourself be present. For once you do not race through contingencies: instead you stack seedlings with someone else's rhythm, laugh when a post tips in a puddle, and accept a thermos that burns your"
    "palm. The tremor of guilt that often runs beneath your skin is quieter tonight, replaced by a fierce, buoyant energy—you are part of a living intervention, not a lone author of policy briefs."
    "Rin Sato slips an arm through yours, lightly, as if to anchor their presence to yours without demanding anything more. The gesture is intimate. It hums through your bones like a tidal pull."
    "There is a choice to be made tomorrow, and the shadow of Elias Hart's campaign glances across this small, bright island of resolve. The work we've done produces data and motion; it produces stories that will"
    "be sung. But it also sharpens the line where decisions must be named and voted on—where the town must weigh immediate, brass promises against slow, living solutions."
    "Your notebook rests against your thigh. In it are numbers and small, hopeful annotations. In the dark across the inlet, the promenade's ads continue their polished litany. The pier's lanterns reflect in puddles like a map of small beacons."
    "The choir slows to a hush, and for an instant you feel the world hold its breath with you—an intake of wind before a long tide."
    "The mud in your nails, the warmth of Rin's arm, the numbers in your notebook—all of it lines up into one fact you cannot deny: tomorrow the town will decide whether it wants to be defended"
    "by concrete or tended like a garden. You have chosen the side of tending; that choice feels like love, like risk, like travail."

    scene bg ch4_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, sustained violin note that brightens and then holds—an invitation to what comes next]

